            <div1 type="enclosure">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.1-4_0003"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">3</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <hi rend="caps">ELEGY TO DOROTHY</hi>
                
                    (To Dorothy Calvin, killed in the Spring of 1959)
                </opener>
                <lg>
                    <l>The bash-box swings low in the sweet chariot</l>
                    <l>And the cocks blow free in a chestnut tree</l>
                        <l>And the elegy lays on a canopy.</l>
                    <l>The City of souls rests turbulently;</l>
                    <l>Hot feet haw the green grass grainery.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>Black birds bustle at a born-again</l>
                    <l>As the sick story cannot remember when</l>
                        <l>The Saturday subterfuge began.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>The sadsongers sniff and snip a snare</l>
                        <l>That ties the tangled tongues that tear</l>
                        <l>The imaginary mien from shoulders; lean</l>
                            <l>one, long one, little one.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>The sapient sun sees no cotton-topped bird</l>
                        <l>from the faraway South,</l>
                    <l>But no limbs care to cover the care-less mouths.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>No more the joking jaspers and coffee-cupped hands</l>
                       <l> bent ' round the laughing squares.</l>
                    <l>The day is gone; the Veiled Prophet ball has bounced away</l>
                        <l>to time-honored memory</l>
                        <l>and leaves</l>
                        <l>the remnants of disintegrating, clandestine self-loves.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>But the snare is snipped and the cloudy clamor of thick thought begins</l>
                        <l>as I search for my way home.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>I could have sworn I walked with you today.</l>
                </lg>
                
                <closer>
                    <signed>william austin martin</signed>--<dateline>july 25, 1959</dateline>
                </closer>
                
